explanation: UT_GetStubEntry and UT_ClearStubEntry: these are the two functions called by the target; their implementations must be inspected to see whether they (directly or via callees) call memcmp to compare null-terminated strings. UT_EntryKey_t and UT_StubTableEntry_t: the type definitions reveal whether keys or entry fields are char* / NUL-terminated strings (which would make any use of memcmp a MISRA violation). UT_ENTRYTYPE_RETVAL_CONFIG_DEFERRED: the constant passed to UT_GetStubEntry may alter internal code paths (e.g. selecting a string-keyed lookup), so its definition is needed to follow control flow. memcmp: the standard function must be searched for in the above functions (and their internals) to determine if it is used to compare null-terminated strings.
